The uniform distribution on \((0,1)\) has mean \(\mu = 0.5\) and variance \(\sigma^2 = \frac{1}{12}\). The sample mean \(\bar{X}\) for a sample of size \(n = 12\) has mean \(\mu_{\bar{X}} = \mu = 0.5\) and variance \(\sigma_{\bar{X}}^2 = \frac{\sigma^2}{n} = \frac{1/12}{12} = \frac{1}{144}\). Thus, the standard deviation is \(\sigma_{\bar{X}} = \frac{1}{12}\).

By the Central Limit Theorem, \(\bar{X}\) is approximately normally distributed. The probability is standardized using the z-score formula \(Z = \frac{\bar{X} - 0.5}{1/12}\).

