For each drug, the number of successes follows a binomial distribution with parameters \(n = 10\) and \(p = 0.7\). The probability that the number of successes for a single drug is at most 8 is \(P(S \leq 8)\). This is calculated as \(1 - P(S = 9) - P(S = 10)\).

- \(P(S = 10) = (0.7)^{10} = 0.0282475249\)
- \(P(S = 9) = \binom{10}{9} (0.7)^9 (0.3) = 10 \times 0.040353607 \times 0.3 = 0.121060821\)
- \(P(S > 8) = P(S = 9) + P(S = 10) = 0.121060821 + 0.0282475249 = 0.1493083459\)
- \(P(S \leq 8) = 1 - 0.1493083459 = 0.8506916541\)

Since the successes for the three drugs are independent, the probability that all three drugs have at most 8 successes is \([P(S \leq 8)]^3 = (0.8506916541)^3\).

- \((0.8506916541)^2 = 0.7236762901\)
- \((0.7236762901) \times 0.8506916541 = 0.6156253803\)

Thus, \(P(\text{all } S_i \leq 8) = 0.6156253803\).

The probability that the maximum number of successes exceeds 8 is the complement:
- \(P(\max S_i > 8) = 1 - P(\text{all } S_i \leq 8) = 1 - 0.6156253803 = 0.3843746197\)

