********
**************
* RESPONSE 1 *
**************
The solution calculates \(D_e\) by adding the zero-point energy (ZPE) to \(D_0\). The ZPE is computed using the formula \(\frac{1}{2} \omega_e - \frac{1}{4} \omega_e x_e\), with \(\omega_e = 1405.65  \text{cm}^{-1}\) and \(\omega_e x_e = 23.20  \text{cm}^{-1}\), resulting in ZPE = \(697.025  \text{cm}^{-1}\). This is converted to eV using the factor \(1  \text{cm}^{-1} = 1.23984 \times 10^{-4}  \text{eV}\), giving ZPE = \(0.086420  \text{eV}\). Adding this to \(D_0 = 2.4287  \text{eV}\) yields \(D_e = 2.515120  \text{eV}\), which is rounded to four decimal places as \(2.5151  \text{eV}\) to match the precision of \(D_0\).

The final answer, as stated in the solution, is \(2.5151\).

